  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Harvard College Courses: What is general shopping advice for Turkish classes?",
  "response": "When considering Turkish classes at Harvard College or any other institution, here are some general shopping tips to keep in mind:\n\n1. **Determine Your Level**: Assess your current proficiency in Turkish. Are you a complete beginner, or do you have some prior knowledge? Most institutions offer classes that cater to different levels, so choose one that matches your skills.\n\n2. **Check Course Descriptions**: Review the course syllabus and descriptions carefully. Look for information on the curriculum, teaching methods, and the focus of the class (e.g., conversation, grammar, reading, writing).\n\n3. **Instructor Qualifications**: Research the instructors teaching the course. Look for their qualifications, teaching experience, and familiarity with the Turkish language and culture. Faculty profiles are often available on the department's website.\n\n4. **Class Size and Format**: Consider the size of the class. Smaller classes can provide more individualized attention. Also, check whether the course is offered in person, online, or in a hybrid format, depending on your learning preference.\n\n5. **Course Materials**: Investigate the textbooks and resources used in the class. Ensure they are current and comprehensive. Sometimes, instructors may also provide supplementary materials.\n\n6. **Student Reviews**: Seek out reviews or testimonials from previous students who have taken the course. This feedback can provide insights into the course's strengths and weaknesses.\n\n7. **Office Hours and Supplemental Support**: Check if the instructor offers office hours or supplement sessions. Extra support can be valuable if you need help outside of class.\n\n8. **Cultural Exposure**: Consider if the course includes cultural components, such as films, literature, or history, as understanding the cultural context can enhance your language learning experience.\n\n9. **Credit and Transferability**: If you're considering taking Turkish for credit, verify how it fits into your academic plan and whether it can be transferred to other institutions if needed.\n\n10. **Cost and Financial Aid**: Be mindful of the cost of the classes and any fees associated with them, as well as financial aid options available to you.\n\nRemember to reflect on your goals for learning Turkish\u2014whether for travel, academic purposes, or personal interest\u2014so that you can choose a class that aligns with your objectives.",
